Project Overview

Introduction

For this project, I wanted to explore dispararities in the population of men and women across Germany. I have frequently heard about the flight of women from rural communities, especially in the former East, being a contributing factor to depression and economic inertia in these areas, so I was curious if the data would support this story.

Data Sources

I acquired data on the population breakdown for individual Landkreisen (this is a NUTS-3 designation, similar to the US county level) via the German statistics portal, Destatis: https://www.destatis.de/DE/Startseite.html. Unfortunately, their site does not allow me to provide a direct link to the data source, but it can be found via the table code 12411-0016 (Bevlkerung: Kreise, Stichtag, Geschlecht) and 12411-0018 (Bevlkerung: Kreise, Stichtag, Geschlecht, Altersgruppen).

The shapefile I acquired from the Bundesamt fr Kartographie und Geodsie and can be downloaded here: http://www.geodatenzentrum.de/geodaten/gdz_rahmen.gdz_div?gdz_spr=deu&gdz_akt_zeile=5&gdz_anz_zeile=1&gdz_unt_zeile=19&gdz_user_id=0

Mapping the Disparaties

Overall Population

To start out with, I wanted to first get a picture of how gender disparities vary across Germany irrespective of age. The difference mapped here is the percentage of men living in a given Landkreis minus the percentage of women living in that same Landkreis. The difference is calculated as the percentage of a population that is male minus the percentage of the population that is female. A more negative number represents a more female-skewing Landkreis, and a more positive number represents a more male-skewing Landkreis.

As the scale shows (ranging from -5 percent to 2.5 percent), the overall variation in the difference between the male and female populations in a given Landkreis doesnt vary hugely. Rhe most female-skewing Landkreis, Landau in der Pfalz in the state of Rheinland-Pfalz, has a 5 percent difference between the male and female populations. The most male-skewing Landkreis, Dingolfing-Landau in the state of Bavaria, has a 3 percent difference between the male and female populations. All in all, these numbers arent particularly dramatic. The map generally shows a fair amount of variation across Germany, although overall Germany largely skews slightly female, with approximately 85 percent of all Landkreisen having slightly to somewhat more women than men.

Adults aged 18-35

But to me, the most interesting variation to look at is not the overall disparities across Germany. When we break up the data into age groups, we can explore specific trends that are tied to stages of life. I wanted to specifically focus on the 18-35 bracket, because this is an age range where many people are moving to new locations for educational or work opportunities (or both, since Germany has a great apprenticeship system), as well as an age range where many people are seeking out and establishing romantic partnerships. How do these trends vary when looking just as this specific age bracket?

The first thing you might notice when you compare the map showing gender ratios for the 18-35 age bracket with the map for Germanys overall population is that this is a much darker map, suggesting there are both stronger and more widespread male-skewing regions in this age bracket. You see this reflected in the averages of the two datasets for the overall dataset, the average Landkreis is 49.4 percent male. In the 18-35 dataset, the average Landkreis is 52.5 percent male.

However, I didnt like how this map displayed the overall variation across Germany I felt like the continuous color scale made it hard to see just how much or how sharply one Landkreis might differ from another. To address this, I made a second map for the 18-35 age brack, this one with a discrete color scale where I could manually set the breaks in the scale. In this map, each consecutive darker shade represents an increase of 4 percentage points.

The choice to manually code breaks into the scale comes with the risk of critique that Im simply manipulating the data until it shows what I want it to. I personally find it defensible, since I think it helps highlight the more interesting parts of the map without presenting a completely false picture, but its understandble if others disagree (and thats why I thought it was also important to first include how the map looks when viewed with a continuous scale).

Here the most extreme cases i.e., the most male- and female-skewing Landkreisen are easier to discern. In particular, its easier to see that much of the former East Germany is sharply male-skewing, including multiple Landkreisen with the male population exceeding the female population by 10 pecent or even more. However, this is definitely not a trend that is solely present in East Germany: most of the Landkreisen in Germany have slightly to moderately more men than women, and Southern Germany especially displays several Landkreisen with at least 6 percent more men than women.

Lets look at a few of the more striking cases.

If you know anything about Germany, youll notice pretty quickly that there are a lot of familiar names cropping up in this list: cities like Bonn, Dsseldorf, Munich, Cologne and Frankfurt, AKA some of Germanys largest cities. Many other familiar cities (like Berlin or Nuremberg) dont show up in this table, but only because they are just barely skewing male. In general, we observe that large cities tend to either have largely balanced male-to-female ratios, or they skew slightly to moderately female.

OK, but Landau in der Pfalz??

Topping the above table of female-skewing Landkreisen is Landau in der Pfalz, a town toward Germanys southwest with 46,000 total inhabitants. Why is such a random-seeming place the most female-skewing Landkreis by far within 18-35 age bracket?

My Technologiestiftung co-worker Ben almost immediately came up with what I think is a sound theory: Laundau is home to a branch of the Unversitt Koblenz-Landau. According to Wikipedia, the main study programs there are teaching, pedagogy, psychology, social sciences, and environmental sciences AKA a lot of fields that are traditionally studied by more women than men. It would take more in-depth research to know how good a theory this is, but at first blush, I think it makes a lot of sense.

Some observations about the most male-skewing Landkreisen:

  • The leading Landkreis, Kaiserslautern, is well-known among Americans for its large American military base. Obviously American service personnel are not included in German population statistics, but I wonder if the base attracts satellite industries related to the military and defense sector that tend to be male-dominated? Additionally, Kaiserslautern is home to a technical university which presumably has more male than female students.
  • The next four leading Landkreisen Ilm, Aachen, Darmstadt, and Karlsruhe are also well-known for their technical universities. Students there will not be the least bit surprised if you tell them they are living in some of the most male-skewing areas in Germany.
  • Dingolfing-Landau, a Landkreis in the south of Germany, is not home to a technical university. It is however located in an area home to many auto manufacturers, including a BMW factory located within the Landkreis.

Key Questions

  1. How does the overall proportion of men and women in a given Landkreis vary across Germany?

  2. How do these proportions differ when looking only at young adults (i.e., 18 - 35 years old)?

  3. What factors are relevant for predicting a larger disparity between men and women?
